fn status_text(status: &Status) -> String {
    if status.busy {
        return non_empty(&status.activity).or_else(|| non_empty(&status.title))
            .unwrap_or_else(|| "working".to_string());
    }
    non_empty(&status.title).unwrap_or_else(|| "idle".to_string())
}
```
`busy` is literally `rec.working` (`src/daemon/server/status_publish.rs:25`), the session row's boolean flag set `true` at `rpc_turn_start` and `false` at `rpc_turn_end` (`src/daemon/server/turns.rs:38, 194`). So "@codex working" means: the daemon's session row for @codex had `working=1` at the time its last kind:30315 heartbeat was cached, and that row hasn't expired (NIP-40 `expiration`, TTL below). If `activity`/`title` (from the `src/distill` module) are non-empty they override the literal string "working"/"idle". [...] **Liveness/threshold**: a status row counts only while `now <= expiration` (`status.rs:93-101`, `live_status_for_channel`). `expiration = now + STATUS_TTL_SECS` where `STATUS_TTL_SECS = 90` (`src/domain.rs:14`), re-armed every `HEARTBEAT_SECS = 30` (`src/domain.rs:16`, `status_publish.rs:78`) for any session that is `working` or heartbeated within the TTL window. A stale (>90s silent) agent simply disappears from `<members>`/`<recent-presence>` — no explicit "offline" marker beyond the default fallback string `"offline"` used when a pubkey has no status row at all (`people.rs:31`).
